# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gif-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gif-format/animated-png] The first frame of an APNG file is stored as a normal PNG stream, so most standard PNG decoders are able to display the first frame of an APNG file.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] The frame speed data and all of the subsequent frames are stored in extra chunks (as provided for by the original PNG specification).
[src:gif-format/animated-png] APNG competed with Multiple-image Network Graphics (MNG), a comprehensive format for bitmapped animations which was created in 2001 by the same team as PNG, which is now obsolete.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] APNG's advantages over MNG are its smaller library size and its compatibility with older PNG implementations.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] The APNG specification was created in 2004 by Stuart Parmenter and Vladimir Vukićević of the Mozilla Corporation to allow for storing the animations needed for interfaces such as throbbers.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] In May 2003, Mozilla had scrapped support for MNG animations, which provides a superset of APNG functionality, citing concerns about the large file size required for the expansive MNG decoder library (300 KB); the APNG decoder, built on the back of the PNG decoder, was a much smaller component.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] Among users and maintainers of the PNG and MNG formats, APNG had a lukewarm reception.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] In particular, PNG was conceived to be a single-image format.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] APNG hides the subsequent frames in PNG ancillary chunks in such a way that APNG-unaware applications would ignore them, but there are otherwise no changes to the format to allow software to distinguish between animated and non-animated images.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] Some of the main concerns arising from this were the inability of applications to negotiate for PNG and APNG, or distinguish between PNG and APNG once received, or for legacy software to even inform users that there are additional frames.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] The PNG Development Group rejected APNG as an official extension on 20 April 2007, and there have been several subsequent proposals for a simple animated graphics format based on PNG using several different approaches.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] The Candidate Recommendation was published on 21 September 2023.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] On 24 June 2025 it was finally elevated to the Recommendation final status by the W3C.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] Sequence numbers apply to both frame control and frame data chunks, which together follow a common sequence, thus enabling the order and timing of frames to be recovered should an APNG-unaware PNG editor re-order them as allowed by PNG chunk ordering rules.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] Frames utilize the same bit depth, color type, compression method, filter method, interlace method, and palette (if any) as the default image.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] An application reading a PNG file is meant to ignore any chunks which it does not understand, making APNG backwards compatible.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] Applications without support for the APNG extension show only the first frame, disregarding the rest of the frames.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] Animated stickers for Signal are APNG with some restrictions (the size of the file is limited to 300kb, the length of the animation is limited to 3 seconds and, visibly (this last point is unclear), the resolution must be 512x512px).
[src:gif-format/animated-png] Mozilla Firefox added support for APNG in version 3 trunk builds on 23 March 2007.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] However, because libpng is the PNG Group's reference implementation of the official specification, APNG support was not added prior to version 1.8 of the main libpng distribution since it was unratified by the Group before.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] Iceweasel 3 supports APNG by using Mozilla's unofficial variant of libpng.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] In 2008 WorldDMB adopted APNG as a backward compatible extension to enable animation as part of the MOT SlideShow user application for Digital Radio.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] "APNG 1.0 Specification - Animated Portable Network Graphics" is included as normative Annex A in the ETSI standard TS 101 499 V2.2.1.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] In 2016, Apple adopted the APNG format as the preferred format for animated stickers in iOS 10 iMessage apps.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] On 15 March 2017, APNG support was added to Chromium.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] A server-side library exists that allows web browsers that support the canvas tag, but do not support APNG, to display APNGs.
[src:gif-format/animated-png] Examples of such browsers include Microsoft Edge Legacy and Internet Explorer 9.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Color depth is only one aspect of color representation, expressing the precision with which the amount of each primary can be expressed; the other aspect is how broad a range of colors can be expressed (the gamut).
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The definition of both color precision and gamut is accomplished with a color encoding specification which assigns a digital code value to a location in a color space.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The number of bits of resolved intensity in a color channel is also known as **radiometric resolution**, especially in the context of satellite images.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] With the relatively low color depth, the stored value is typically a number representing the index into a color map or palette (a form of vector quantization).
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The colors available in the palette itself may be fixed by the hardware or modifiable by software.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Modifiable palettes are sometimes referred to as pseudocolor palettes.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Old graphics chips, particularly those used in home computers and video game consoles, often have the ability to use a different palette per sprites and tiles in order to increase the maximum number of simultaneously displayed colors, while minimizing use of then-expensive memory (and bandwidth).
[src:gif-format/color-depth] For example, in the ZX Spectrum the picture is stored in a two-color format, but these two colors can be separately defined for each rectangular block of 8×8 pixels.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The palette itself has a color depth (number of bits per entry).
[src:gif-format/color-depth] While the best VGA systems only offered an 18-bit (262,144 color) palette from which colors could be chosen, all color Macintosh video hardware offered a 24-bit (16 million color) palette.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] 24-bit palettes are nearly universal on any recent hardware or file format using them.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] If instead the color can be directly figured out from the pixel values, it is "direct color".
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Palettes were rarely used for depths greater than 12 bits per pixel, as the memory consumed by the palette would exceed the necessary memory for direct color on every pixel.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] 2 colors, often black and white direct color.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Sometimes 1 meant black and 0 meant white, the inverse of modern standards.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Most of the first graphics displays were of this type, the X Window System was developed for such displays, and this was assumed for a 3M computer.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] In the late 1980s there were professional displays with resolutions up to 300 dpi (the same as a contemporary laser printer) but color proved more popular.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] 4 colors, usually from a selection of fixed palettes.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Gray-scale early NeXTstation, color Macintoshes, Atari ST medium resolution.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] 8 colors, almost always all combinations of full-intensity red, green, and blue.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Many early home computers with TV displays, including the ZX Spectrum and BBC Micro.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] 16 colors, usually from a selection of fixed palettes.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Used by IBM CGA (at the lowest resolution), EGA, and by the least common denominator VGA standard at higher resolution.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Color Macintoshes, Atari ST low resolution, Commodore 64, and Amstrad CPCs also supported 4-bit color.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] 32 colors from a programmable palette, used by the Original Amiga chipset.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Used by the Master System, Enhanced Graphics Adapter, GIME for TRS-80 Color Computer 3, Pebble Time smartwatch (64 color e-paper display), and Parallax Propeller using the reference VGA circuit.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] 256 colors, usually from a fully-programmable palette: Most early color Unix workstations, Super VGA, color Macintosh, Atari TT, Amiga AGA chipset, Falcon030, Acorn Archimedes.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Both X and Windows provided elaborate systems to try to allow each program to select its own palette, often resulting in incorrect colors in any window other than the one with focus.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Some systems placed a color cube in the palette for a direct-color system (and so all programs would use the same palette).
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Usually fewer levels of blue were provided than others, since the normal human eye is less sensitive to the blue component than to either red or green (two thirds of the eye's receptors process the longer wavelengths).
[src:gif-format/color-depth] 4,096 colors, usually from a fully-programmable palette (though it was often set to a 16×16×16 color cube).
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Some Silicon Graphics systems, Color NeXTstation systems, and Amiga systems in HAM mode have this color depth.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] RGBA4444, a related 16 bpp representation providing the color cube and 16 levels of transparency, is a common texture format in mobile graphics.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] In high-color systems, two bytes (16 bits) are stored for each pixel.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Most often, each component (R, G, and B) is assigned 5 bits, plus one unused bit (or used for a mask channel or to switch to indexed color); this allows 32,768 colors to be represented.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] However, an alternate assignment which reassigns the unused bit to the G channel allows 65,536 colors to be represented, but without transparency.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] These color depths are sometimes used in small devices with a color display, such as mobile phones, and are sometimes considered sufficient to display photographic images.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Among the first hardware to use the standard were the Sharp X68000 and IBM's Extended Graphics Array (XGA).
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The term "high color" has recently been used to mean color depths greater than 24 bits.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] More expensive LCDs (typically IPS) can display 24-bit color depth or greater.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] 24 bits almost always use 8 bits each of R, G, and B (8 bpc).
[src:gif-format/color-depth] As of 2018, 24-bit color depth is used by virtually every computer and phone display and the vast majority of image storage formats.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Almost all cases of 32 bits per pixel assigns 24 bits to the color, and the remaining 8 for the alpha channel (transparency) or left unused.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] While human eye can discriminate up to ten million colors, color gamuts employed by displays are typically smaller than the range of human vision.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] This means that 24 bits should be able to differentiate different colors with enough precision to prevent the perception of banding.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] However, displays do not evenly distribute the colors in human perception space, so banding between some adjacent colors can still be perceived.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The DVD-Video and Blu-ray Disc standards support a bit depth of 8 bits per color in YCbCr with 4:2:0 chroma subsampling.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] YCbCr can be losslessly converted to RGB.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] macOS and Classic Mac OS refer to 24-bit color as "millions" of colors.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The term *true color* is sometimes used to mean what this article calls *direct color*.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] It is also often used to refer to all color depths greater than or equal to 24 bits.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Some earlier systems placed three 10-bit channels in a 32-bit word, with 2 bits unused (or used as a 4-level alpha channel); the Cineon file format, for example, used this.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Some SGI systems had 10-bit (or more) digital-to-analog converters for the video signal and could be set up to interpret data stored this way for display.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] BMP files define this as one of its formats, and it is called "HiColor" by Microsoft.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Video cards with 10 bits per component started coming to market in the late 1990s.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] An early example was the Radius ThunderPower card for the Macintosh, which included extensions for QuickDraw and Adobe Photoshop plugins to support editing 30-bit images.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Some vendors call their 24-bit color depth with FRC panels 30-bit panels; however, true deep color displays have 10-bit or more color depth without FRC.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The HDMI 1.3 specification defines a bit depth of 30 bits (as well as 36 and 48 bit depths).
[src:gif-format/color-depth] As of 2026, 30 and 36 bit output is supported by all modern GPUs from Nvidia, AMD and Intel.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] At WinHEC 2008, Microsoft announced that color depths of 30 bits and 48 bits would be supported in Windows 7, along with the wide color gamut scRGB.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC or H.265) defines the Main 10 profile, which allows for 8 or 10 bits per sample with 4:2:0 chroma subsampling.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The Main 10 profile was added at the October 2012 HEVC meeting based on proposal JCTVC-K0109 which proposed that a 10-bit profile be added to HEVC for consumer applications.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The proposal stated that this was to allow for improved video quality and to support the Rec.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] 2020 color space that will be used by UHDTV.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The second version of HEVC has five profiles that allow for a bit depth of 8 bits to 16 bits per sample.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Using 12 bits per color channel produces 36 bits, 68,719,476,736 colors.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] If an alpha channel of the same size is added then there are 48 bits per pixel.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] If an alpha channel of the same size is added then there are 64 bits per pixel.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Some systems started using those bits for numbers outside the 0–1 range rather than for increasing the resolution.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Numbers greater than 1 were for colors brighter than the display could show, as in high-dynamic-range imaging (HDRI).
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Negative numbers can increase the gamut to cover all possible colors, and for storing the results of filtering operations with negative filter coefficients.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The Pixar Image Computer used 12 bits to store numbers in the range [-1.5, 2.5), with 2 bits for the integer portion and 10 for the fraction.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The Cineon imaging system used 10-bit professional video displays with the video hardware adjusted so that a value of 95 was black and 685 was white.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The amplified signal tended to reduce the lifetime of the CRT.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] More bits also encouraged the storage of light as linear values, where the number directly corresponds to the amount of light emitted.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Linear levels makes calculation of computer graphics much easier.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] However, linear color results in disproportionately more samples near white and fewer near black, so the quality of 16-bit linear is about equal to 12-bit sRGB.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Floating point numbers can represent linear light levels spacing the samples semi-logarithmically.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Floating point representations also allow for drastically larger dynamic ranges as well as negative values.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Most systems first supported 32-bit per channel single-precision, which far exceeded the accuracy required for most applications.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] In 1999, Industrial Light & Magic released the open standard image file format OpenEXR which supported 16-bit-per-channel half-precision floating-point numbers.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] At values near 1.0, half precision floating point values have only the precision of an 11-bit integer value, leading some graphics professionals to reject half-precision in situations where the extended dynamic range is not needed.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Virtually all television displays and computer displays form images by varying the strength of just three primary colors: red, green, and blue.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] For example, bright yellow is formed by roughly equal red and green contributions, with no blue contribution.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] For storing and manipulating images, alternative ways of expanding the traditional triangle exist: One can convert image coding to use fictitious primaries, that are not physically possible but that have the effect of extending the triangle to enclose a much larger color gamut.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] An equivalent, simpler change is to allow negative numbers in color channels, so that the represented colors can extend out of the color triangle formed by the primaries.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] However these only extend the colors that can be represented in the image encoding; neither trick extends the gamut of colors that can actually be rendered on a display device.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Supplementary colors can widen the color gamut of a display, since it is no longer limited to the interior of a triangle formed by three primaries at its corners, e.g. the CIE 1931 color space.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Recent technologies such as Texas Instruments's *BrilliantColor* augment the typical red, green, and blue channels with up to three other primaries: cyan, magenta, and yellow.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Cyan would be indicated by negative values in the red channel, magenta by negative values in the green channel, and yellow by negative values in the blue channel, validating the use of otherwise fictitious negative numbers in the color channels.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Mitsubishi and Samsung (among others) use *BrilliantColor* in some of their TV sets to extend the range of displayable colors.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The Sharp Aquos line of televisions has introduced Quattron technology, which augments the usual RGB pixel components with a yellow subpixel.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] However, formats and media that allow or make use of the extended color gamut are at present extremely rare.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] Because humans are overwhelmingly trichromats or dichromats one might suppose that adding a fourth "primary" color could provide no practical benefit.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] However humans can see a broader range of colors than a mixture of three colored lights can display.
[src:gif-format/color-depth] The deficit of colors is particularly noticeable in saturated shades of bluish green (shown as the left upper grey part of the horseshoe in the diagram) of RGB displays: Most humans can see more vivid blue-greens than any color video screen can display.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The **Graphics Interchange Format** (**GIF**; /ɡɪf/ *GHIF* or /dʒɪf/ *JIF*, ) is a bitmap image format that was developed by a team at the online services provider CompuServe led by American computer scientist Steve Wilhite and released on June 15, 1987.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The format can contain up to 8 bits per pixel, allowing a single image to reference its own palette of up to 256 different colors chosen from the 24-bit RGB color space.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] It can also represent multiple images in a file, which can be used for animations, and allows a separate palette of up to 256 colors for each frame.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] These palette limitations make GIF less suitable for reproducing color photographs and other images with color gradients, but well-suited for simpler images such as graphics or logos with solid areas of color.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] GIF images are compressed using the Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) lossless data compression technique to reduce the file size without degrading the visual quality.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In this context, short video clips are sometimes termed "GIFs" despite having no relation to the original file format.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] CompuServe introduced GIF on 15 June 1987 to provide a color image format for their file downloading areas.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] This replaced their earlier run-length encoding format, which was black and white only.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] GIF became popular because it used Lempel–Ziv–Welch data compression.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Since this was more efficient than the run-length encoding used by PCX and MacPaint, fairly large images could be downloaded reasonably quickly even with slow modems.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The original version of GIF was called 87a.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] This version already supported multiple images in a stream.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The two versions can be distinguished by looking at the first six bytes of the file (the "magic number" or signature), which, when interpreted as ASCII, read "GIF87a" or "GIF89a", respectively.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] CompuServe encouraged the adoption of GIF by providing downloadable conversion utilities for many computers.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] By December 1987, for example, an Apple IIGS user could view pictures created on an Atari ST or Commodore 64.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] GIF was one of the first two image formats commonly used on Web sites, the other being the black-and-white XBM.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In September 1995, Netscape Navigator 2.0 added the ability for animated GIFs to loop.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] While GIF was developed by CompuServe, it used the Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) lossless data compression algorithm patented by Unisys in 1985.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Controversy over the licensing agreement between Unisys and CompuServe in 1994 spurred the development of the Portable Network Graphics (PNG) standard.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In 2004, all patents relating to the proprietary compression used for GIF expired.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The feature of storing multiple images in one file, accompanied by control data, is used extensively on the Web to produce simple animations.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The optional interlacing feature, which stores image scan lines out of order in such a fashion that even a partially downloaded image was somewhat recognizable, also helped GIF's popularity, as a user could abort the download if it was not what was required.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In May 2015 Facebook added support for GIF.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In 2014, Twitter, also added support to GIF as well as Instagram in 2018.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In 2016, the Internet Archive released a searchable library of GIFs from their GeoCities archive.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] As a noun, the word *GIF* is found in the newer editions of many dictionaries.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In 2012, the American wing of the Oxford University Press recognized *GIF* as a verb as well, meaning "to create a GIF file", as in "GIFing was the perfect medium for sharing scenes from the Summer Olympics".
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The press's lexicographers voted it their word of the year, saying that GIFs have evolved into "a tool with serious applications including research and journalism".
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The pronunciation of the first letter of *GIF* has been disputed since the 1990s.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The most common pronunciations in English are /dʒɪf/ ⓘ (with a soft *g* as in *gin*) and /ɡɪf/ ⓘ (with a hard *g* as in *gift*), differing in the phoneme represented by the letter *G*.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] However, the word is widely pronounced as /ɡɪf/, with a hard *g*, and polls have generally shown that this hard *g* pronunciation is more prevalent.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The disagreement over the pronunciation has led to a heated Internet debate.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] On the occasion of receiving a lifetime achievement award at the 2013 Webby Awards ceremony, Wilhite publicly rejected the hard-*g* pronunciation; his speech led to more than 17,000 posts on Twitter and dozens of news articles.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The White House and the TV program *Jeopardy!* also entered the debate in 2013.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Smucker Company, the owners of the Jif brand, partnered with the animated image database and search engine Giphy to release a limited-edition "Jif vs.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] GIF" (hashtagged as #JIFvsGIF) jar of peanut butter that had a label humorously declaring the soft-*g* pronunciation to refer exclusively to the peanut butter, and *GIF* to be exclusively pronounced with the hard-*g* pronunciation.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] GIFs are suitable for sharp-edged line art with a limited number of colors, such as logos.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] This takes advantage of the format's lossless compression, which favors flat areas of uniform color with well-defined edges.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] They can also be used to store low-color sprite data for games.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] GIFs can be used for small animations and low-resolution video clips, or as reactions in online messaging used to convey emotion and feelings in moving pictures.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] They are popular on social media platforms such as Tumblr, Facebook, and X (formerly known as Twitter).
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Conceptually, a GIF file describes a fixed-sized graphical area (the "logical screen") populated with zero or more "images".
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Many GIF files have a single image that fills the entire logical screen.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Others divide the logical screen into separate sub-images.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The images may also function as animation frames in an animated GIF file, but again, these need not fill the entire logical screen.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] GIF files start with a fixed-length header ("GIF87a" or "GIF89a") giving the version, followed by a fixed-length Logical Screen Descriptor giving the pixel dimensions and other characteristics of the logical screen.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The screen descriptor may also specify the presence and size of a Global Color Table (GCT), which follows next if present.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] An image starts with a fixed-length Image Descriptor, which may specify the presence and size of a Local Color Table (which follows next if present).
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The image data follows: one byte giving the bit width of the unencoded symbols (which must be at least 2 bits wide, even for bi-color images), followed by a series of sub-blocks containing the LZW-encoded data.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Extension blocks (blocks that "extend" the 87a definition via a mechanism already defined in the 87a spec) consist of the sentinel, an additional byte specifying the type of extension, and a series of sub-blocks with the extension data.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Extension blocks that modify an image (like the Graphic Control Extension that specifies the optional animation delay time and optional transparent background color) must immediately precede the segment with the image they refer to.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Each sub-block begins with a byte giving the number of subsequent data bytes in the sub-block (1 to 255).
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The series of sub-blocks is terminated by an empty sub-block (a 0-byte).
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] This structure allows the file to be parsed even if not all parts are understood.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] A GIF marked 87a may contain extension blocks; the intent is that a decoder can read and display the file without the features covered in extensions it does not understand.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The full details of the file format are covered in the GIF specification.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] GIF is palette-based: the colors used in an image (a frame) in the file have their RGB values defined in a palette table that can hold up to 256 entries, and the data for the image refer to the colors by their indices (0–255) in the palette table.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The color definitions in the palette can be drawn from a color space of millions of shades (224 shades, 8 bits for each primary), but the maximum number of colors a frame can use is 256.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] This limitation was reasonable when GIF was developed because hardware that could display more than 256 colors simultaneously was rare.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Simple graphics, line drawings, cartoons, and grey-scale photographs typically need fewer than 256 colors.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Each frame can designate one index as a "transparent background color": any pixel assigned this index takes on the color of the pixel in the same position from the background, which may have been determined by a previous frame of animation.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Many techniques, collectively called dithering, have been developed to approximate a wider range of colors with a small color palette by using pixels of two or more colors to approximate in-between colors.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] These techniques sacrifice spatial resolution to approximate deeper color resolution.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] While not part of the GIF specification, dithering can be used in images subsequently encoded as GIF images.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] This is often not an ideal solution for GIF images, both because the loss of spatial resolution typically makes an image look fuzzy on the screen, and because the dithering patterns often interfere with the compressibility of the image data, working against GIF's main purpose.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In the early days of graphical web browsers (1981-1987, see Graphics Processing Unit), graphics cards with 8-bit buffers (allowing only 256 colors) were common and it was fairly common to make GIF images using the websafe palette.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] This ensured predictable display, but severely limited the choice of colors.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] When 24-bit color became the norm, palettes could instead be populated with the optimum colors for individual images.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] A small color table may suffice for small images, and keeping the color table small allows the file to be downloaded faster.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Both the 87a and 89a specifications allow color tables of 2*n* colors for any *n* from 1 through 8.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Most graphics applications will read and display GIF images with any of these table sizes; but some do not support all sizes when *creating* images.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Tables of 2, 16, and 256 colors are widely supported.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Although GIF is almost never used for true color images, it is possible to do so.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] A GIF image can include multiple image blocks, each of which can have its own 256-color palette, and the blocks can be tiled to create a complete image.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Alternatively, the GIF89a specification introduced the idea of a "transparent" color where each image block can include its own palette of 255 visible colors plus one transparent color.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] A complete image can be created by layering image blocks, with the visible portion of each layer showing through the transparent portions of the layers above.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] To render a full-color image as a GIF, the original image must be broken down into smaller regions having no more than 255 or 256 different colors.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Each of these regions is then stored as a separate image block with its own local palette, and when the image blocks are displayed together (either by tiling or by layering partially transparent image blocks), the complete, full-color image appears.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] For example, breaking an image into tiles of 16 by 16 pixels (256 pixels in total) ensures that no tile has more than the local palette limit of 256 colors, although larger tiles may be used and similar colors merged, resulting in some loss of color information.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Since each image block can have its own local color table, a GIF file having many image blocks can be very large, limiting the usefulness of full-color GIFs.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Additionally, not all GIF rendering programs handle tiled or layered images correctly.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Many rendering programs interpret tiles or layers as animation frames and display them in sequence as an animation with most web browsers automatically displaying the frames with a delay time of 0.1 seconds or more.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The hex numbers in the following tables are in little-endian byte order, as the format specification prescribes.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The image pixel data, scanned horizontally from top left, are converted by LZW encoding to codes that are then mapped into bytes for storing in the file.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Each subsequent code is stored starting at the least significant bit not already used.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] This byte stream is stored in the file as a series of "sub-blocks".
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Each sub-block has a maximum length of 255 bytes and is prefixed with a byte indicating the number of data bytes in the sub-block.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The series of sub-blocks is terminated by an empty sub-block (a single 0 byte, indicating a sub-block with 0 data bytes).
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] For the sample image above, the reversible mapping between 9-bit codes and bytes is shown below.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] A slight compression is evident: pixel colors defined initially by 15 bytes are exactly represented by 12 code bytes, including control codes.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The encoding process that produces the 9-bit codes is shown below.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] A local string accumulates pixel color numbers from the palette, with no output action, as long as the local string can be found in a code table.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] There is special treatment of the first two pixels that arrive before the table grows from its initial size by additions of strings.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] After each output code, the local string is initialized to the latest pixel color (that could not be included in the output code).
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] For clarity, the table is shown above as being built of strings of increasing length.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] That scheme can function, but the table consumes an unpredictable amount of memory.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Memory can be saved in practice by noting that each new string to be stored consists of a previously stored string augmented by one character.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] It is economical to store at each address only two words: an existing address and one character.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The LZW algorithm requires a search of the table for each pixel.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] A linear search through up to 4096 addresses would make the coding slow.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In practice, the codes can be stored in order of numerical value; this allows each search to be done by a SAR (Successive Approximation Register, as used in some ADCs), with only 12 magnitude comparisons.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] For this efficiency, an extra table is needed to convert between codes and actual memory addresses; the extra table upkeep is needed only when a new code is stored, which happens at a much lower rate than pixel rate.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Decoding begins by mapping the stored bytes back to 9-bit codes.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] These are decoded to recover the pixel colors as shown below.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Shorter code lengths can be used for palettes smaller than the 256 colors in the example.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] If the palette is only 64 colors (so color indexes are 6 bits wide), the symbols can range from 0 to 63, and the symbol width can be taken to be 6 bits, with codes starting at 7 bits.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In fact, the symbol width need not match the palette size: as long as the values decoded are always less than the number of colors in the palette, the symbols can be any width from 2 to 8, and the palette size any power of 2 from 2 to 256.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] For example, if only the first four colors (values 0 to 3) of the palette are used, the symbols can be taken to be 2 bits wide with codes starting at 3 bits.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Conversely, the symbol width could be set at 8, even if only values 0 and 1 are used; these data would only require a two-color table.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Although there would be no point in encoding the file that way, something similar typically happens for bi-color images: the minimum symbol width is 2, even if only values 0 and 1 are used.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The code table initially contains codes that are one bit longer than the symbol size in order to accommodate the two special codes *clr* and *end* and codes for strings that are added during the process.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] When the table is full, the code length increases to give space for more strings, up to a maximum code of 4095 = FFF(hex).
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] As the decoder builds its table, it tracks these increases in code length, and it is able to unpack incoming bytes accordingly.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The GIF encoding process can be modified to create a file without LZW compression that is still viewable as a GIF image.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] This technique was introduced originally as a way to avoid patent infringement.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Uncompressed GIF can also be a useful intermediate format for a graphics programmer because individual pixels are accessible for reading or painting.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] An uncompressed GIF file can be converted to an ordinary GIF file simply by passing it through an image editor.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The modified encoding method ignores building the LZW table and emits only the root palette codes and the codes for CLEAR and STOP.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] This yields a simpler encoding (a 1-to-1 correspondence between code values and palette codes) but sacrifices all of the compression: each pixel in the image generates an output code indicating its color index.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] When processing an uncompressed GIF, a standard GIF decoder will not be prevented from writing strings to its dictionary table, but the code width must never increase since that triggers a different packing of bits to bytes.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] If the symbol width is n, the codes of width *n*+1 fall naturally into two blocks: the lower block of 2*n* codes for coding single symbols, and the upper block of 2*n* codes that will be used by the decoder for sequences of length greater than one.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Of that upper block, the first two codes are already taken: 2*n* for CLEAR and 2*n* + 1 for STOP.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The decoder must also be prevented from using the last code in the upper block, 2*n*+1 − 1, because when the decoder fills that slot, it will increase the code width.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Thus, in the upper bloc,k there are 2*n* − 3 codes available to the decoder that won't trigger an increase in code width.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Because the decoder is always one step behind in maintaining the table, it does not generate a table entry upon receiving the first code from the encoder, but it will generate one for each succeeding code.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Thus, the encoder can generate 2*n* − 2 codes without triggering an increase in code width.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Therefore, the encoder must emit extra CLEAR codes at intervals of 2*n* − 2 codes or fewer to make the decoder reset the coding dictionary.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The GIF standard allows such extra CLEAR codes to be inserted in the image data at any time.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The composite data stream is partitioned into sub-blocks that each carry from 1 to 255 bytes.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] For the sample 3×5 image above, the following 9-bit codes represent "clear" (100) followed by image pixels in scan order and "stop" (101).
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The trivial example of a large image of solid color demonstrates the variable-length LZW compression used in GIF files.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The code values shown are packed into bytes, which are then packed into blocks of up to 255 bytes.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] A block of image data begins with a byte that declares the number of bytes to follow.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The last block of data for an image is marked by a zero block-length byte.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The GIF Specification allows each image within the logical screen of a GIF file to specify that it is interlaced; i.e., that the order of the raster lines in its data block is not sequential.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] This allows a partial display of the image that can be recognized before the full image is painted.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The pixels within each line are not interlaced, but presented consecutively from left to right.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] As with non-interlaced images, there is no break between the data for one line and the data for the next.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The indicator that an image is interlaced is a bit set in the corresponding Image Descriptor block.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Although GIF was not designed as an animation medium, its ability to store multiple images in one file naturally suggested using the format to store the frames of an animation sequence.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] To facilitate *displaying* animations, the GIF89a spec added the Graphic Control Extension (GCE), which allows the images (frames) in the file to be painted with time delays, forming a video clip.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Each frame in an animation GIF is introduced by its own GCE specifying the time delay to wait after the frame is drawn.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Global information at the start of the file applies by default to all frames.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The data is stream-oriented, so the file offset of the start of each GCE depends on the length of preceding data.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Within each frame, the LZW-coded image data is arranged in sub-blocks of up to 255 bytes; the size of each sub-block is declared by the byte that precedes it.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] By default, an animation displays the sequence of frames only once, stopping when the last frame is displayed.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] To enable an animation to loop, Netscape in the 1990s used the Application Extension block (intended to allow vendors to add application-specific information to the GIF file) to implement the Netscape Application Block (NAB).
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] This block, placed immediately before the sequence of animation frames, specifies the number of times the sequence of frames should be played (1 to 65535 times) or that it should repeat continuously (zero indicates loop forever).
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Support for these repeating animations first appeared in Netscape Navigator version 2.0, and then spread to other browsers.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Most browsers now recognize and support NAB, though it is not strictly part of the GIF89a specification.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The following example shows the structure of the animation file *Rotating earth (large).gif* shown (as a thumbnail) in the article's infobox.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The animation delay for each frame is specified in the GCE in hundredths of a second.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Some economy of data is possible where a frame needs only to rewrite a few of the pixels on the display, because the Image Descriptor can define a smaller rectangle to be rescanned instead of the whole image.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Browsers or other displays that do not support animated GIFs typically show only the first frame.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The size and color quality of animated GIF files can vary significantly depending on the application used to create them.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] More advanced techniques involve modifying color sequences to better match the existing LZW dictionary, a form of lossy compression.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Simply packing a series of independent frame images into a composite animation tends to yield large file sizes.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Tools are available to minimize the file size of an existing GIF.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Metadata can be stored in GIF files as a comment block, a plain text block, or an application-specific application extension block.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Several graphics editors use unofficial application extension blocks to include the data used to generate the image, so that it can be recovered for further editing.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] All of these methods technically require the metadata to be broken into sub-blocks so that applications can navigate the metadata block without knowing its internal structure.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The Extensible Metadata Platform (XMP) metadata standard introduced an unofficial but now widespread "XMP Data" application extension block for including XMP data in GIF files.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Since the XMP data is encoded using UTF-8 without NUL characters, there are no 0 bytes in the data.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Rather than break the data into formal sub-blocks, the extension block terminates with a "magic trailer" that routes any application treating the data as sub-blocks to a final 0 byte that terminates the sub-block chain.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In 1977 and 1978, Jacob Ziv and Abraham Lempel published a pair of papers on a new class of lossless data-compression algorithms, now collectively referred to as LZ77 and LZ78.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In 1983, Terry Welch developed a fast variant of LZ78 which was named Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW).
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Welch filed a patent application for the LZW method in June 1983.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The resulting patent, US4558302, granted in December 1985, was assigned to Sperry Corporation who subsequently merged with Burroughs Corporation in 1986 and formed Unisys.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Further patents were obtained in the United Kingdom, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and Canada.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In June 1984, an article by Welch was published in the IEEE magazine, which publicly described the LZW technique for the first time.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] LZW became a popular data compression technique and, when the patent was granted, Unisys entered into licensing agreements with over a hundred companies.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The popularity of LZW led CompuServe to choose it as the compression technique for their version of GIF, developed in 1987.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] At the time, CompuServe was not aware of the patent.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Unisys became aware that the version of GIF used the LZW compression technique and entered into licensing negotiations with CompuServe in January 1993.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The subsequent agreement was announced on 24 December 1994.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Following this announcement, there was widespread condemnation of CompuServe and Unisys, and many software developers threatened to stop using GIF.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The PNG format (see below) was developed in 1995 as an intended replacement.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] However, obtaining support from the makers of Web browsers and other software for the PNG format proved difficult, and it was not possible to replace GIF, although PNG has gradually increased in popularity.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Therefore, GIF variations without LZW compression were developed.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] For instance the libungif library, based on Eric S.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Raymond's giflib, allows creation of GIFs that followed the data format but avoided the compression features, thus avoiding use of the Unisys LZW patent.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Dobb's* article described a way to achieve LZW-compatible encoding for data that would compress well under a run-length encoding mechanism without infringing on its patents.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] In August 1999, Unisys changed the details of its licensing practice, announcing the option for owners of certain non-commercial and private websites to obtain licenses on payment of a one-time license fee of $5000 or $7500.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Such licenses were not required for website owners or other GIF users who had used licensed software to generate GIFs.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Nevertheless, Unisys was subjected to thousands of online attacks and abusive emails from users believing that they were going to be charged $5000 or sued for using GIFs on their websites.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The United States LZW patent expired on 20 June 2003.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] The counterpart patents in the United Kingdom, France, Germany, and Italy expired on 18 June 2004, the Japanese patents expired on 20 June 2004, and the Canadian patent expired on 7 July 2004.
[src:gif-format/gif-p01] Consequently, while Unisys has further patents and patent applications relating to improvements to the LZW technique, LZW itself (and consequently GIF) have been free to use since July 2004.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] Portable Network Graphics (PNG) was designed as a replacement for GIF to avoid infringement of Unisys' patent on the LZW compression technique.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] PNG offers better compression and more features than GIF, animation being the only significant exception.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] PNG is more suitable than GIF in instances where true-color imaging and alpha transparency are required.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] Although support for PNG format came slowly, new web browsers support PNG.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] Older versions of Internet Explorer do not support all features of PNG.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] Versions 6 and earlier do not support alpha channel transparency without using Microsoft-specific HTML extensions.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] Gamma correction of PNG images was not supported before version 8, and the display of these images in earlier versions may have the wrong tint.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] For identical 8-bit (or lower) image data, PNG files are typically smaller than the equivalent GIFs, due to the more efficient compression techniques used in PNG encoding.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] Complete support for GIF is complicated chiefly by the complex canvas structure it allows, though this is what enables the compact animation features.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] Videos resolve many issues that GIFs present through common usage on the web.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] They include drastically smaller file sizes, the ability to surpass the 8-bit color restriction, and better frame-handling and compression through inter-frame coding.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] Virtually universal support for the GIF format in web browsers, and a lack of official support for video in the HTML standard, caused GIF to rise to prominence for the purpose of displaying short video-like files on the web.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] The PNG group officially rejected APNG as an official extension on 20 April 2007.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] There have been several subsequent proposals for a simple animated graphics format based on PNG using several different approaches.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] APNG is currently supported by all major web browsers including Chrome (since version 59.0), Opera, Firefox and Edge.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] Compared to the GIF format, which lacks DCT compression, HEIF allows significantly more efficient compression.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] HEIF stores more information and produces higher-quality animated images at a small fraction of an equivalent GIF's size.
[src:gif-format/gif-p02] In April 2014, 4chan added support for silent WebM videos that are under 3 MB in size and 2 min in length, and in October 2014, Imgur started converting any GIF files uploaded to the site to H.264 video and giving the link to the HTML player the appearance of an actual file with a `.gifv` extension.
[src:gif-format/lzw] A large English text file can typically be compressed via LZW to about half its original size.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The algorithm became the first widely used universal data compression method used on computers.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The algorithm was used in the compress program commonly included in Unix systems starting around 1986.
[src:gif-format/lzw] It has since disappeared from many distributions, because it both infringed the LZW patent and because gzip produced better compression ratios using the LZ77-based DEFLATE algorithm.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The algorithm found wide use when it became part of the GIF image format in 1987.
[src:gif-format/lzw] It may optionally be used in TIFF and PDF files.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Although LZW is available in Adobe Acrobat software, Acrobat by default uses DEFLATE for most text and color-table-based image data in PDF files.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The scenario described by Welch's 1984 paper encodes sequences of 8-bit data as fixed-length 12-bit codes.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The codes from 0 to 255 represent 1-character sequences consisting of the corresponding 8-bit character, and the codes 256 through 4095 are created in a dictionary for sequences encountered in the data as it is encoded.
[src:gif-format/lzw] At each stage in compression, input bytes are gathered into a sequence until the next character would make a sequence with no code yet in the dictionary.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The code for the sequence (without that character) is added to the output, and a new code (for the sequence with that character) is added to the dictionary.
[src:gif-format/lzw] In the practical application of image compression and for an image based on a color table, a natural character alphabet is the set of color table indexes.
[src:gif-format/lzw] In the 1980s, many images had small color tables (on the order of 16 colors).
[src:gif-format/lzw] When the maximum code value is reached, encoding proceeds using the existing table, but new codes are not generated for addition to the table.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The clear code lets the table be reinitialized after it fills up, which lets the encoding adapt to changing patterns in the input data.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Smart encoders can monitor the compression efficiency and clear the table whenever the existing table no longer matches the input well.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Since codes are added in a manner determined by the data, the decoder mimics building the table as it sees the resulting codes.
[src:gif-format/lzw] It is critical that the encoder and decoder agree on the variety of LZW used: the size of the alphabet, the maximum table size (and code width), whether variable-width encoding is used, initial code size, and whether to use the clear and stop codes (and what values they have).
[src:gif-format/lzw] Most formats that employ LZW build this information into the format specification or provide explicit fields for them in a compression header for the data.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Find the longest string **W** in the dictionary that matches the current input.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Emit the dictionary index for **W** to output and remove **W** from the input.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Add **W** followed by the next symbol in the input to the dictionary.
[src:gif-format/lzw] A dictionary is initialized to contain the single-character strings corresponding to all the possible input characters (and nothing else except the clear and stop codes if they're being used).
[src:gif-format/lzw] The algorithm works by scanning through the input string for successively longer substrings until it finds one that is not in the dictionary.
[src:gif-format/lzw] When such a string is found, the index for the string without the last character (i.e., the longest substring that *is* in the dictionary) is retrieved from the dictionary and sent to output, and the new string (including the last character) is added to the dictionary with the next available code.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The last input character is then used as the next starting point to scan for substrings.
[src:gif-format/lzw] In this way, successively longer strings are registered in the dictionary and available for subsequent encoding as single output values.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The algorithm works best on data with repeated patterns, so the initial parts of a message see little compression.
[src:gif-format/lzw] As the message grows, however, the compression ratio tends asymptotically to the maximum (i.e., the compression factor or ratio improves on an increasing curve, and not linearly, approaching a theoretical maximum inside a limited time period rather than over infinite time).
[src:gif-format/lzw] If the symbol is not encoded in the dictionary, goto step 7.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Emit the corresponding string **W** to output.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Concatenate the previous string emitted to output with the first symbol of **W**; add this to the dictionary.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Concatenate the previous string emitted to output with its first symbol; call this string **V**.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Add **V** to the dictionary and emit **V** to output.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The decoding algorithm works by reading a value from the encoded input and outputting the corresponding string from the dictionary.
[src:gif-format/lzw] However, the full dictionary is not needed, only the initial dictionary that contains single-character strings (and that is usually hard coded in the program, instead of sent with the encoded data).
[src:gif-format/lzw] The decoder then proceeds to the next input (which was already read in the previous iteration) and processes it as before, and so on until it has exhausted the input stream.
[src:gif-format/lzw] If variable-width codes are being used, the encoder and decoder must be careful to change the width at the same points in the encoded data so they don't disagree on boundaries between individual codes in the stream.
[src:gif-format/lzw] In the standard version, the encoder increases the width from *p* to *p* + 1 when a sequence ω + *s* is encountered that is not in the table (so that a code must be added for it) but the next available code in the table is 2*p* (the first code requiring *p* + 1 bits).
[src:gif-format/lzw] The encoder emits the code for ω at width *p* (since that code does not require *p* + 1 bits), and then increases the code width so that the next code emitted is *p* + 1 bits wide.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The decoder is always one code behind the encoder in building the table, so when it sees the code for ω, it generates an entry for code 2*p* − 1.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Since this is the point where the encoder increases the code width, the decoder must increase the width here as well—at the point where it generates the largest code that fits in *p* bits.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Unfortunately, some early implementations of the encoding algorithm increase the code width and *then* emit ω at the new width instead of the old width, so that to the decoder it looks like the width changes one code too early.
[src:gif-format/lzw] This is called "early change"; it caused so much confusion that Adobe now allows both versions in PDF files, but includes an explicit flag in the header of each LZW-compressed stream to indicate whether early change is being used.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Of the graphics file formats that support LZW compression, TIFF uses early change, while GIF and most others don't.
[src:gif-format/lzw] When the table is cleared in response to a clear code, both encoder and decoder change the code width after the clear code back to the initial code width, starting with the code immediately following the clear code.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Since the codes emitted typically do not fall on byte boundaries, the encoder and decoder must agree on how codes are packed into bytes.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The two common methods are *LSB-first* ("least significant bit first") and *MSB-first* ("most significant bit first").
[src:gif-format/lzw] MSB-first packing aligns the first code so that its *most* significant bit falls in the MSB of the first stream byte, with overflow aligned with the MSB of the next byte; further codes are written with MSB going into the most significant bit not yet used in the current stream byte.
[src:gif-format/lzw] TIFF files and PDF files use MSB-first packing order.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Many applications extend the algorithm by applying further encoding to the sequence of output symbols.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Some package the coded stream as printable characters using some form of binary-to-text encoding.
[src:gif-format/lzw] This increases the encoded length and decreases the compression rate.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Conversely, increased compression can often be achieved with an *adaptive entropy encoder*.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Such a coder estimates the probability distribution for the value of the next symbol, based on the observed frequencies of values so far.
[src:gif-format/lzw] A standard entropy encoding such as Huffman coding or arithmetic coding then uses shorter codes for values with higher probabilities.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The following example illustrates the LZW algorithm in action, showing the status of the output and the dictionary at every stage, both in encoding and decoding the data.
[src:gif-format/lzw] This example has been constructed to give reasonable compression on a very short message.
[src:gif-format/lzw] In real text data, repetition is generally less pronounced, so longer input streams are typically necessary before the compression builds up efficiency.
[src:gif-format/lzw] There are 26 symbols in the plaintext alphabet (the capital letters *A* through *Z*).
[src:gif-format/lzw] *#* is used to represent a stop code: a code outside the plaintext alphabet that triggers special handling.
[src:gif-format/lzw] We arbitrarily assign these the values 1 through 26 for the letters, and 0 for the stop code '#'.
[src:gif-format/lzw] (Most flavors of LZW would put the stop code *after* the data alphabet, but nothing in the basic algorithm requires that.
[src:gif-format/lzw] A computer renders these as strings of bits.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Five-bit codes are needed to give sufficient combinations to encompass this set of 27 values.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The dictionary is initialized with these 27 values.
[src:gif-format/lzw] As the dictionary grows, the codes must grow in width to accommodate the additional entries.
[src:gif-format/lzw] A 5-bit code gives 25 = 32 possible combinations of bits, so when the 33rd dictionary word is created, the algorithm must switch at that point from 5-bit strings to 6-bit strings (for *all* code values, including those previously output with only five bits).
[src:gif-format/lzw] Note that since the all-zero code 00000 is used, and is labeled "0", the 33rd dictionary entry is labeled **32**.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Buffer input characters in a sequence ω until ω + next character is not in the dictionary.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Emit the code for ω, and add ω + next character to the dictionary.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Start buffering again with the next character.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Encoded length = (6 codes × 5 bits/code) + (11 codes × 6 bits/code) = 96 bits.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Using LZW has saved 29 bits out of 125, reducing the message by more than 23%.
[src:gif-format/lzw] If the message were longer, then the dictionary words would begin to represent longer and longer sections of text, sending repeated words very compactly.
[src:gif-format/lzw] To decode an LZW-compressed archive, one needs to know in advance the initial dictionary used, but additional entries can be reconstructed as they are always simply concatenations of previous entries.
[src:gif-format/lzw] At each stage, the decoder receives a code X; it looks X up in the table and outputs the sequence χ it codes, and it conjectures χ + ? as the entry the encoder just added – because the encoder emitted X for χ precisely because χ + ? was not in the table, and the encoder goes ahead and adds it.
[src:gif-format/lzw] It is the first letter in the sequence coded by the *next* code Z that the decoder receives.
[src:gif-format/lzw] So the decoder looks up Z, decodes it into the sequence ω and takes the first letter z and tacks it onto the end of χ as the next dictionary entry.
[src:gif-format/lzw] This works as long as the codes received are in the decoder's dictionary, so that they can be decoded into sequences.
[src:gif-format/lzw] What happens if the decoder receives a code Z that is not yet in its dictionary?
[src:gif-format/lzw] Since the decoder is always just one code behind the encoder, Z can be in the encoder's dictionary only if the encoder *just* generated it, when emitting the previous code X for χ.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The decoder knows that the encoder just added Z as a code for χ + some unknown character *c*, so ω = χ + *c*.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Since *c* is the first character in the input stream after χ, and since ω is the string appearing immediately after χ, *c* must be the first character of the sequence ω.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Since χ is an initial substring of ω, *c* must also be the first character of χ.
[src:gif-format/lzw] So even though the Z code is not in the table, the decoder is able to infer the unknown sequence and adds χ + (the first character of χ) to the table as the value of Z.
[src:gif-format/lzw] This situation occurs whenever the encoder encounters input of the form *cScSc*, where *c* is a single character, *S* is a string and *cS* is already in the dictionary, but *cSc* is not.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The encoder emits the code for *cS*, putting a new code for *cSc* into the dictionary.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Next it sees *cSc* in the input (starting at the second *c* of *cScSc*) and emits the new code it just inserted.
[src:gif-format/lzw] The argument above shows that whenever the decoder receives a code not in its dictionary, the situation must look like this.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Although input of form *cScSc* might seem unlikely, this pattern is fairly common when the input stream is characterized by significant repetition.
[src:gif-format/lzw] In particular, long strings of a single character (which are common in the kinds of images LZW is often used to encode) repeatedly generate patterns of this sort.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Various patents have been issued in the United States and other countries for LZW and similar algorithms.
[src:gif-format/lzw] LZ78 was covered by U.S. patent 4,464,650 by Lempel, Ziv, Cohn, and Eastman, assigned to Sperry Corporation, later Unisys Corporation, filed on August 10, 1981.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Two US patents were issued for the LZW algorithm: U.S. patent 4,814,746 by Victor S.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Wegman and assigned to IBM, originally filed on June 1, 1983, and U.S. patent 4,558,302 by Welch, assigned to Sperry Corporation, later Unisys Corporation, filed on June 20, 1983.
[src:gif-format/lzw] In addition to the above patents, Welch's 1983 patent also includes citations to several other patents that influenced it, including two 1980 Japanese patents (JP9343880A and JP17790880A) from NEC's Jun Kanatsu, U.S. patent 4,021,782 (1974) from John S.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Holtz, and a 1981 German patent (DE19813118676) from Karl Eckhart Heinz.
[src:gif-format/lzw] In 1993–94, and again in 1999, Unisys Corporation received widespread condemnation when it attempted to enforce licensing fees for LZW in GIF images.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Unisys's US patent on the LZW algorithm expired on June 20, 2003, 20 years after it had been filed.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Patents that had been filed in the United Kingdom, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and Canada all expired in 2004, likewise 20 years after they had been filed.
[src:gif-format/lzw] LZMW (1985), by Victor Miller and Mark Wegman, searches input for the longest string already in the dictionary (the "current" match) and then adds the concatenation of the previous match with the current match to the dictionary.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Dictionary entries thus grow more rapidly, but this scheme is much more complicated to implement.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Miller and Wegman suggest deleting low-frequency entries from the dictionary when the dictionary fills up.
[src:gif-format/lzw] LZAP (1988), by James Storer, is a modification of LZMW.
[src:gif-format/lzw] Instead of adding just the concatenation of the previous match with the current match to the dictionary, add the concatenations of the previous match with each initial substring of the current match ("AP" stands for "all prefixes").
[src:gif-format/lzw] For example, if the previous match is "wiki" and current match is "pedia", then the LZAP encoder adds 5 new sequences to the dictionary: "wikip", "wikipe", "wikiped", "wikipedi", and "wikipedia", where the LZMW encoder adds only the one sequence "wikipedia".
[src:gif-format/lzw] This eliminates some of the complexity of LZMW, at the price of adding more dictionary entries.
[src:gif-format/lzw] LZWL is a syllable-based variant of LZW.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] In computer graphics and digital photography, a **raster graphic**, **raster image**, or simply **raster** is a digital image made up of a rectangular grid of tiny colored (usually square) so-called pixels.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Unlike vector graphics which use mathematical formulas to describe shapes and lines, raster images store the exact color of each pixel, making them ideal for photographs and images with complex colors and details.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Raster images are characterized by their dimensions (width and height in pixels) and color depth (the number of bits per pixel).
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] They can be displayed on computer displays, printed on paper, or viewed on other media, and are stored in various image file formats.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The printing and prepress industries know raster graphics as **contones** (from "continuous tones").
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] In contrast, *line art* is usually implemented as vector graphics in digital systems.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Many raster manipulations map directly onto the mathematical formalisms of linear algebra, where mathematical objects of matrix structure are of central concern.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Raster or **gridded data** may be the result of a gridding procedure.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The word "raster" has its origins in the Latin *rastrum* (a rake), which is derived from *radere* (to scrape).
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] It originates from the raster scan of cathode-ray tube (CRT) video monitors, which draw the image line by line by magnetically or electrostatically steering a focused electron beam.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] By association, it can also refer to a rectangular grid of pixels.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The modern word rastrum refers to a device for drawing musical staff lines.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The fundamental strategy underlying the raster data model is the tessellation of a plane, into a two-dimensional array of squares, each called a *cell* or *pixel* (from "picture element").
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] In digital photography, the plane is the visual field as projected onto the image sensor; in computer art, the plane is a virtual canvas; in geographic information systems, the plane is a projection of the Earth's surface.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The size of each square pixel, known as the *resolution* or *support*, is constant across the grid.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] A single numeric value is then stored for each pixel.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] For most images, this value is a visible color, but other measurements are possible, even numeric codes for qualitative categories.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Each raster grid has a specified *pixel format*, the data type for each number.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Common pixel formats are binary, grayscale, palettized, and full-color, where color depth determines the fidelity of the colors represented, and color space determines the range of color coverage (which is often less than the full range of human color vision).
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Most modern color raster formats represent color using 24 bits (over 16 million distinct colors), with 8 bits (values 0–255) for each color channel (red, green, and blue).
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The digital sensors used for remote sensing and astronomy are often able to detect and store wavelengths beyond the visible spectrum; the large CCD bitmapped sensor at the Vera C.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Rubin Observatory captures 3.2 gigapixels in a single image (6.4 GB raw), over six color channels which exceed the spectral range of human color vision.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Most computer images are stored in raster graphics formats or compressed variations, including GIF, JPEG, and PNG, which are popular on the World Wide Web.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] A **raster data** structure is based on a (usually rectangular, square-based) tessellation of the 2D plane into cells, each containing a single value.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] To store the data in a file, the two-dimensional array must be serialized.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The most common way to do this is a *row-major* format, in which the cells along the first (usually top) row are listed left to right, followed immediately by those of the second row, and so on.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] In the example at right, the cells of tessellation A are overlaid on the point pattern B resulting in an array C of quadrant counts representing the number of points in each cell.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] For purposes of visualization a lookup table has been used to color each of the cells in an image D.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] To reconstruct the two-dimensional grid, the file must include a *header* section at the beginning that contains at least the number of columns, and the pixel datatype (especially the number of bits or bytes per value) so the reader knows where each value ends to start reading the next one.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Headers may also include the number of rows, georeferencing parameters for geographic data, or other metadata tags, such as those specified in the Exif standard.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] High-resolution raster grids contain a large number of pixels, and thus consume a large amount of storage.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] This has led to multiple approaches to compressing the data volume into smaller files.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The most common strategy is to look for patterns or trends in the pixel values, then store a parameterized form of the pattern instead of the original data.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Common raster compression algorithms include run-length encoding (RLE), JPEG, LZ (the basis for PNG and ZIP), Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) (the basis for GIF), and others.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] For example, Run length encoding looks for repeated values in the array, and replaces them with the value and the number of times it appears.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] This technique is very efficient when there are large areas of identical values, such as a line drawing, but in a photograph where pixels are usually slightly different from their neighbors, the RLE file would be up to twice the size of the original.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Some compression algorithms, such as RLE and LZW, are *lossless*, where the original pixel values can be perfectly regenerated from the compressed data.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Other algorithms, such as JPEG, are *lossy*, because the parameterized patterns are only an approximation of the original pixel values, so the latter can only be estimated from the compressed data.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Vector images (line work) can be rasterized (converted into pixels), and raster images vectorized (raster images converted into vector graphics), by software.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] In both cases, some information is lost, although certain vectorization operations can recreate salient information, as in the case of optical character recognition.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Early mechanical televisions developed in the 1920s employed rasterization principles.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Electronic television based on cathode-ray tube displays are raster scanned with horizontal rasters painted left to right, and the raster lines painted top to bottom.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Modern flat-panel displays such as LED monitors still use a raster approach.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Each on-screen pixel directly corresponds to a small number of bits in memory.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The screen is refreshed simply by scanning through pixels and coloring them according to each set of bits.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The refresh procedure, being speed critical, is often implemented by dedicated circuitry, often as a part of a graphics processing unit.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Using this approach, the computer contains an area of memory that holds all the data that are to be displayed.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The central processor writes data into this region of memory and the video controller collects them from there.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The bits of data stored in this block of memory are related to the eventual pattern of pixels that will be used to construct an image on the display.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] An early scanned display with raster computer graphics was invented in the late 1960s by A.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Michael Noll at Bell Labs, but its patent application filed February 5, 1970, was abandoned at the Supreme Court in 1977 over the issue of the patentability of computer software.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] During the 1970s and 1980s, pen plotters, using vector graphics, were common for creating precise drawings, especially on large format paper.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] However, since then almost all printers create the printed image as a raster grid, including both laser and inkjet printers.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] When the source information is vector, rendering specifications and software such as PostScript are used to create the raster image.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Three-dimensional voxel raster graphics are employed in video games and are also used in medical imaging such as MRI scanners.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Geographic phenomena are commonly represented in a raster format in GIS.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The raster grid is *georeferenced*, so that each pixel (commonly called a *cell* in GIS because the "picture" part of "pixel" is not relevant) represents a square region of geographic space.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] The value of each cell then represents some measurable (qualitative or quantitative) property of that region, typically conceptualized as a field.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Examples of fields commonly represented in rasters include: temperature, population density, soil moisture, land cover, surface elevation, etc.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Two sampling models are used to derive cell values from the field: in a *lattice*, the value is measured at the center point of each cell; in a *grid*, the value is a summary (usually a mean or mode) of the value over the entire cell.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Raster graphics are resolution dependent, meaning they cannot scale up to an arbitrary resolution without loss of apparent quality.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] This property contrasts with the capabilities of vector graphics, which easily scale up to the quality of the device rendering them.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Raster graphics deal more practically than vector graphics with photographs and photo-realistic images, while vector graphics often serve better for typesetting or for graphic design.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Typically, a resolution of 150 to 300 PPI works well for 4-color process (CMYK) printing.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] However, for printing technologies that perform color mixing through dithering (halftone) rather than through overprinting (virtually all home/office inkjet and laser printers), printer DPI and image PPI have a very different meaning, and this can be misleading.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Because, through the dithering process, the printer builds a single image pixel out of several printer dots to increase color depth, the printer's DPI setting must be set far higher than the desired PPI to ensure sufficient color depth without sacrificing image resolution.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Thus, for instance, printing an image at 250 PPI may actually require a printer setting of 1200 DPI.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] When an image is rendered in a raster-based image editor, the image is composed of millions of pixels.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] At its core, a raster image editor works by manipulating each individual pixel.
[src:gif-format/raster-graphics] Most pixel-based image editors work using the RGB color model, but some also allow the use of other color models, such as the CMYK color model.
